org.jdom2.output
Class AbstractSAXOutputProcessor

java.lang.Object
  org.jdom2.output.AbstractOutputProcessor
      org.jdom2.output.AbstractSAXOutputProcessor
All Implemented Interfaces:
JDOMConstants, SAXOutputProcessor
public class AbstractSAXOutputProcessor
extends AbstractOutputProcessor
implements SAXOutputProcessor, JDOMConstants

Outputs a JDOM document as a stream of SAX2 events.

Most ContentHandler callbacks are supported. Neither ignorableWhitespace() nor skippedEntity() have been implemented.

At this time, it is not possible to access notations and unparsed entity references in a DTD from JDOM. Therefore, DTDHandler callbacks have not been implemented yet.

The ErrorHandler callbacks have not been implemented, since these are supposed to be invoked when the document is parsed and at this point the document exists in memory and is known to have no errors.

Author:
Brett McLaughlin, Jason Hunter, Fred Trimble, Bradley S. Huffman, Rolf Lear

printContent

protected void printContent(SAXOutputProcessor.SAXTarget out,
                            FormatStack fstack,
                            NamespaceStack nstack,
                            java.util.List<? extends Content> content)
                     throws org.xml.sax.SAXException
This will handle printing of a List of Content.

The list of Content is basically processed as one of three types of content

  1. Consecutive text-type (Text, CDATA, and EntityRef) content
  2. Stand-alone text-type content
  3. Non-text-type content.
Although the code looks complex, the theory is conceptually simple:
  1. identify one of the three types (consecutive, stand-alone, non-text)
  2. do indent if any is specified.
  3. send the type to the respective print* handler (e.g. #printTextConsecutive(SAXTarget, FormatStack, List, int, int), #printCDATA(SAXTarget, FormatStack, CDATA), or #printComment(SAXTarget, FormatStack, Comment),
  4. do a newline if one is specified.
  5. loop back to 1. until there's no more content to process.

Parameters:
out - SAXTarget to use.
fstack - the FormatStack
nstack - the NamespaceStack
content - List of Content to write.
Throws:
org.xml.sax.SAXException - if the destination SAXTarget fails

printTextConsecutive

protected void printTextConsecutive(SAXOutputProcessor.SAXTarget out,
                                    FormatStack fstack,
                                    java.util.List<? extends Content> content,
                                    int offset,
                                    int len)
                             throws org.xml.sax.SAXException
This will handle printing of a consecutive sequence of text-type Content (CDATA Text, or EntityRef) nodes. It is an error (unspecified Exception or unspecified behaviour) to pass this method any other type of node.

It is a requirement for this method that at least one of the specified text-type instances has non-whitespace, or, put the other way, if all specified text-type values are all white-space only, then you may get odd looking XML (empty lines).

Parameters:
out - SAXTarget to use.
fstack - the FormatStack
content - List of Content to write.
offset - index of first content node (inclusive).
len - number of nodes that are text-type.
Throws:
org.xml.sax.SAXException - if the destination SAXTarget fails

helperTextType

protected final void helperTextType(SAXOutputProcessor.SAXTarget out,
                                    FormatStack fstack,
                                    java.util.List<? extends Content> content,
                                    int offset,
                                    int len)
                             throws org.xml.sax.SAXException
This helper determines how much text-type content there is to print. If there is a single node only, then it is dispatched to the respective print* method, otherwise it is dispatched to the printTextConsecutive method.

It is a requirement for this method that at least one of the specified text-type instances has non-whitespace, or, put the other way, if all specified text-type values are all white-space only, then you may get odd looking XML (empty lines).

Odd things can happen too if the len is <= 0;

Parameters:
out - where to write
fstack - the current FormatStack
content - The list of Content to process
offset - The offset of the first text-type content in the sequence
len - the number of text-type content in the sequence
Throws:
org.xml.sax.SAXException - if the output fails.
